nullq-qns
=========

Docker image that wraps the nullq QUIC implementation [4] for the official
QUIC interoperability test runner [1] and its companion network simulator [2].
Public test results are published at [3].

The image bundles a single Zig-built binary (`qns-endpoint`, sourced from
nullq's `interop/qns_endpoint.zig`) on top of the upstream
`martenseemann/quic-network-simulator-endpoint:latest` base. Both server
and client roles speak HTTP/0.9 over QUIC v1 with ALPN `hq-interop`.
The entrypoint forwards `SSLKEYLOGFILE` and `QLOGDIR` to the endpoint so
runner traces can include Wireshark-compatible TLS secrets and nullq
qlog-style key lifecycle JSONL files.

Files
-----

    Dockerfile            multi-stage build that clones nullq from GitHub
                          and produces /qns-endpoint (boringssl-zig is fetched
                          by Zig from the URL pin in nullq's build.zig.zon)
    Dockerfile.local      local-development build that uses a local nullq
                          context through a Docker named build context
    run_endpoint.sh       entrypoint that maps the runner's TESTCASE/ROLE
                          environment to qns-endpoint flags
    Makefile              docker build / push helpers
    .github/workflows/    CI that rebuilds and publishes the image to
                          ghcr.io/nullstyle/nullq-qns when nullq changes
    README                this file

Build
-----

    make build              # local image as nullq-qns:latest
    make build-local        # local image as nullq-qns:local from ../nullq

Override the upstream source or pin a specific commit with --build-arg:

    docker build \
        --build-arg NULLQ_REF=v0.1.0 \
        -t nullq-qns:custom .

Available build args:

    ZIG_VERSION             zig toolchain to download (default 0.16.0)
    NULLQ_REPO/NULLQ_REF    nullq git url and ref (default main)

The boringssl-zig version is determined by the URL+hash pin in nullq's
build.zig.zon — to bump it, change the pin in nullq, not here.

Runner registration
-------------------

The implementation entry for `quic-interop-runner` should be:

    "nullq": {
      "image": "ghcr.io/nullstyle/nullq-qns:latest",
      "url": "https://github.com/nullstyle/nullq",
      "role": "both"
    }

Local runner validation
-----------------------

For development before nullq commits are pushed to GitHub, build from the
sibling checkouts and run the official runner through nullq's Zig wrapper:

    make build-local
    make interop
    make interop-client
    make interop-both
    make interop-features

The default `make interop` matrix runs nullq-qns as the server against
`quic-go`, `ngtcp2`, and `quiche` for handshake and transfer. The
`make interop-client` matrix runs nullq-qns as the client against those
external servers, and `make interop-both` runs both directions. The
`make interop-features` target runs the stronger `quic-go` server-side
feature gate: handshake, transfer, chacha20, retry, resumption,
zerortt, and multiplexing.

Defaults assume this workspace layout:

    ../nullq
    ../quic-interop-runner

Override `NULLQ_DIR`, `RUNNER_DIR`, `CLIENTS`, `SERVERS`, and `TESTS`
as needed. `make build-local` stages a `git archive` snapshot of nullq
under `.local-context/`, so commit local nullq changes before using
it when you need the image to include them. Zig fetches boringssl-zig
from the URL pin during the in-Docker build. Use
`make clean-local-context` to force a fresh snapshot.

Run locally
-----------

    # server (HTTP/0.9 over QUIC, ALPN hq-interop) on udp/443
    docker run --rm -e ROLE=server \
        -v $PWD/certs:/certs:ro -v $PWD/www:/www:ro \
        -p 4433:443/udp nullq-qns:latest

    # client downloading from a peer
    docker run --rm -e ROLE=client \
        -e SERVER=peer:443 -e SERVER_NAME=peer \
        -e REQUESTS="https://peer:443/index.html" \
        -v $PWD/downloads:/downloads nullq-qns:latest

Supported testcases
-------------------

The handshake, transfer, longrtt, chacha20, multiplexing, retry,
resumption, zerortt, keyupdate, blackhole, handshakeloss, transferloss,
handshakecorruption, and transfercorruption cases are wired through.
Anything else (including versionnegotiation, http3, multiconnect,
connectionmigration, ecn) exits 127 so the runner records it as
'unsupported'.

Trace output
------------

When the runner sets tracing variables, `run_endpoint.sh` passes them to
`qns-endpoint`:

    SSLKEYLOGFILE=/logs/keys.log     # standard TLS key log lines
    QLOGDIR=/logs/qlog               # nullq key lifecycle JSONL traces

Current status
--------------

The standalone `nullq-qns:local` image built from the sibling `nullq`
checkout has passed the official runner with nullq-as-server for:

    quic-go, ngtcp2, quiche: H,D
    quic-go: H,D,C,S,R,Z,M

The local wrapper also supports nullq-as-client private gates. Current
local client-role results are:

    quic-go, ngtcp2, quiche: H,D
    quic-go: H,D,C,S,R,Z,M

The client-role C20 path depends on the boringssl-zig AES-hardware
testing override (commit 8c47b6e and later) so nullq's QNS harness
can produce a deterministic ChaCha-preferred ClientHello on
AES-capable hosts. The URL+hash pin in nullq's build.zig.zon must
reference a boringssl-zig revision that includes this override.
Keep these results local while nullq burns in before any upstream
runner registration.

`nullq-qns:local` should be held to the same bar before publishing a new
image.

[1] https://github.com/marten-seemann/quic-interop-runner
[2] https://github.com/marten-seemann/quic-network-simulator
[3] https://interop.seemann.io
[4] https://github.com/nullstyle/nullq
